---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is SSH config?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'SSH config is a local file, usually ~/.ssh/config, used to store host aliases and connection settings for repeated SSH access.'
      }
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why use SSH host aliases?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Host aliases shorten long connection commands and standardize options like User, Port, and IdentityFile across environments.'
      }
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How do I connect using an SSH config host?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'After saving the host block, connect with ssh <alias> instead of repeating the full ssh user@host -p port command.'
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout title="SSH Config Builder" description="Build reusable SSH config host aliases for Linux and DevOps workflows.">
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="muted">Linux Dork Tools</p>
    <h1>SSH Config Builder</h1>
    <p>Generate maintainable host aliases for faster SSH workflows.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="card prose">
    <h2>Build reliable SSH host aliases for daily work</h2>
    <p>
      SSH config entries save time by replacing long connection commands with short aliases. Instead of typing full
      hostnames, usernames, ports, and key files every time, you define them once and connect consistently.
    </p>
    <p>
      Teams often use this pattern for production hosts, staging servers, and internal jump boxes. A clean
      <code>~/.ssh/config</code> also helps avoid mistakes when multiple environments use different credentials.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you are searching for “ssh config example” or “how to use ssh host alias”, this generator creates a ready block
      that includes HostName, User, Port, IdentityFile, and optional agent forwarding settings.
    </p>
    <p>
      The result is faster and safer Linux operations because your commands become predictable: update one config block,
      then use <code>ssh alias</code> everywhere in scripts, terminals, and documentation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <div class="grid">
      <label>Host alias <input id="host" value="prod-web" /></label>
      <label>HostName <input id="hostname" value="203.0.113.10" /></label>
      <label>User <input id="user" value="ubuntu" /></label>
      <label>Port <input id="port" value="22" /></label>
      <label>IdentityFile <input id="identity" value="~/.ssh/prod_ed25519" /></label>
      <label>ForwardAgent <select id="agent"><option value="yes">yes</option><option value="no" selected>no</option></select></label>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Generated SSH config block</h2>
    <pre id="ssh-output"></pre>
    <pre>Preview
ssh prod-web
scp ./artifact.tar.gz prod-web:/tmp/</pre>
  </section>

  <script src="../../scripts/ssh-config-builder.ts"></script>
  <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)}></script>
  <style>
    .prose p { margin: 0.75rem 0; }
    .grid { display:grid; gap:.65rem; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit,minmax(220px,1fr)); }
    label { display:grid; gap:.35rem; font-weight:600; }
    input, select { border:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--surface); color:var(--text); border-radius:.55rem; padding:.6rem .7rem; font:inherit; }
    pre { margin:0; background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:.65rem; padding:.75rem; white-space:pre-wrap; }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
